# The Zen of Python (PEP 20)

When two ways of writing the same Python disagree, this file is the
tie-breaker. Memorise it.

```
Beautiful is better than ugly.
Explicit is better than implicit.
Simple is better than complex.
Complex is better than complicated.
Flat is better than nested.
Sparse is better than dense.
Readability counts.
Special cases aren't special enough to break the rules.
Although practicality beats purity.
Errors should never pass silently.
Unless explicitly silenced.
In the face of ambiguity, refuse the temptation to guess.
There should be one-- and preferably only one --obvious way to do it.
Although that way may not be obvious at first unless you're Dutch.
Now is better than never.
Although never is often better than *right* now.
If the implementation is hard to explain, it's a bad idea.
If the implementation is easy to explain, it may be a good idea.
Namespaces are one honking great idea -- let's do more of those!
```
— Tim Peters, *PEP 20*

## How this codebase reads each line

- **Beautiful is better than ugly.** Readability is a feature; "clever"
  one-liners that need a paragraph of explanation are not.
- **Explicit is better than implicit.** Type hints on everything public.
  No magic globals, no `from x import *`, no relying on `__init__.py`
  side effects.
- **Simple is better than complex. Complex is better than complicated.**
  Reach for the simplest tool that fits. If a real-world problem is
  inherently complex, model the complexity — don't smear it across the
  codebase as accidental complication.
- **Flat is better than nested.** Early returns over `if/else/if/else`
  pyramids. Module-per-thing over deep packages.
- **Sparse is better than dense.** A blank line between phases of a
  function is free. Use it.
- **Readability counts.** A reader spends 10x the time on code that the
  author spent writing it. Optimise for the reader.
- **Special cases aren't special enough to break the rules.** No
  conditional `# noqa`, no "just this once" `Any`, no isolated style
  islands.
- **Although practicality beats purity.** The above rule has an
  off-switch: ship the thing. Document the deviation.
- **Errors should never pass silently.** No bare `except:`, no
  `except Exception: pass`, no `try: ... except: ... finally: pass`.
  See `code-smells.md` (Catching and Ignoring Exceptions).
- **Unless explicitly silenced.** Suppressing a known, narrow exception
  *with a comment explaining why* is fine. Make the silence loud.
- **In the face of ambiguity, refuse the temptation to guess.** When the
  spec is unclear, ask. When the input is ambiguous, raise. Don't paper
  it over with a sensible default that nobody asked for.
